node.text:
To celebrate @elijahcraig Old-Fashioned Week, Lynnette Marrero (@drinksat6), bar director of Llama San (@llamasannyc), Llama Inn (@llamainnnyc) and Wonderbar (@wonderbarbeacon), shares how to make her Three Bites of the Apple, an Old-Fashioned inspired by autumn in the Hudson Valley. ⁠
Get the recipe at punchdrink.com and learn more about how you can raise an Elijah Craig Bourbon Old-Fashioned to support the bar community at OldFashionedWeek.com.
#punchpartner @elijahcraig #oldfashionedweek @rwcfusa 
#oldfashioned #cocktail #bartender

Welcome to a special charity episode of “Tip Your Bartender” all about Aperitivo to benefit @rwcfusa! This episode supports industry workers in need by raising funds for @rwcfusa. You can make a contribution by going to the link in our profile, or heading over to @rwcfusa. To date, the Bacardi family of brands has contributed over $150,000 to aid in @rwcfusa’s ongoing relief efforts. @martinirossius will continue their support with a donation following this segment. #raiseyourspirits #drinkpunchtyb

node.text: There's a better way to batch and fizz cocktails for a crowd. All you need is a whipped cream dispenser. The kitchen gadget has become an unlikely bar tool, used by professional and home bartenders alike, to make boldly carbonated, small-batch cocktails. For classic cocktails that typically require soda water, such as tequila-sodas and Biciclettas, carbonating with an iSi whipper eliminates the need for mixers altogether and provides a sharper, more even carbonation and the option to make a round of up to four drinks at a time. For bartenders workshopping a drink, it's a great way to do R&D before scaling it up for a draft program. Head to the link in our profile where @bon_vivantito breaks down the process of using an iSi whipper behind the bar. #drinkpunch 📷: @lizzieamunro

node.text: “I wanted to do a dark, stirred cocktail that could transition either to spring or fall,” explains @black_flamingos's of her Boulevardier riff, Midnight, the Stars and You. The drink is named after the closing song from The Shining and features protagonist Jack Torrance’s favorite whiskey: Jack Daniels. She adds adds floral complexity with chamomile liqueur, and balanceds it with the bitter notes of Varnelli Sibilla, “a really intense amaro.” Get the recipe via the link in our profile. #drinkpunch 📷: @lizzieamunro

node.text: Based on a Galliano cocktail from the '70s, @garretjrichard’s Golden Horseshoe makes the case for a stirred tequila-based tiki drink. His savory take calls for the addition of thyme liqueur and saline, which highlight the lemon and black pepper elements of the gin and underscore the vanilla notes in Galliano. Head to the link in bio for the recipe. #drinkpunch 📷: @lizzieamunro⁠

With over 18.4 million global searches in 2020 alone, the late Douglas Ankrah’s Pornstar Martini is officially the most searched cocktail on planet Earth. The Ghana-born, London-based bartender created the decadent mixture of vanilla vodka, passion fruit liqueur and passion fruit purée served with a side of Champagne in 2002. Nearly twenty years later it continues to hold sway. So what gives this provocative 'tini such staying power? @aarongoldfarb investigates at the link in our bio. #drinkpunch #pornstarmartini 🎨: ⁠

node.text: There's a quick and easy way to infuse spirits with with flash-frozen fruit. Known as “jacking,” the technique is inspired by the freeze distillation methods once used to make applejack. @asher52, bartender and owner of @centurygrandphx and @undertowphx, developed the technique to create a deep flavor without muddling fruit. So how does it work? "The ice crystals freeze the juice in place,” explains Asher, “and when it thaws, the ruptured cell walls leak out the juice.” Not only does it expedite flavor extraction, the process results in an exceptionally vibrant color and intensity of flavor. Head to the link in our profile to learn how to do it yourself. Strawberry Fernet-Branca, anyone? #drinkpunch 📷: @lizzieamunro

node.text: At this point in cocktail history, more than two decades into the revival, just about every Golden Age recipe—and Dark Age recipe, for that matter—has been rediscovered, revived and re-introduced to the drinking public. However, a number of recipes have remained unappreciated—seemingly too odd, unlikely or downright weird to warrant a second look. But with a little help from today’s best bartenders, some of these overlooked cocktails—from the tequila and peppermint schnapps-based Hot Pants to the oddball absinthe, yellow Chartreuse and apricot liqueur-based Yellow Parrot—have proved they are worth keeping around. Head to the link in our profile for the D-List Cocktails that are ready for their closeup. #drinkpunch 📷: @lizzieamunro

node.text: The Godfather—just Scotch sweetened with amaretto liqueur—dropped off the radar in recent decades, but with the modest groundswell of bartenders interested in overhauling long-maligned “disco drinks,” it’s found a new audience. From amaro to palo cortado, today's bartenders are tweaking the simple template to add complexity and depth to the OG drink. Head to the link in our profile for more on the Godfather revival. #drinkpunch⁠ 📷: @lizzieamunro

node.text: Bid farewell to sunburn season with @_haylstorm's Coppertone. Combining coconut gin, coconut syrup, lime juice and Aperol, the cocktail "tastes like suntan lotion in the best possible way.” Served on pebbled ice with a float of Angostura bitters, it, aptly, takes on the color of sunburn. node.text: The Martini has enjoyed the spotlight for so long, nearly every one of the drink’s many variations has enjoyed its moment in the sun. But the Turf Club, a mixture of gin, vermouth, maraschino liqueur, absinthe and orange bitters, which predates the Martini and is just as old as the Martinez, has been patiently waiting its turn. The wait may soon be over. A few select, but prominent, bars have taken up the 1880s relic as their own, including the reborn Brooklyn's @gage.and.tollner, Miami's @surfclubrestaurant and @holywatersf in San Francisco. All three establishments have been pleasantly surprised that their beloved obscure drink has also become a favorite with their customers. Head to the link in our profile for more from @robertosimonson on why it's time to join the Turf Club. #drinkpunch 📷: @lizzieamunro
